Abstract = {{Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD) is characterized by emotion
   dysregulation, altered pain processing, dissociation, impulsivity, and
   interpersonal problems. Neuroimaging studies suggest a dysfunctional
   network including limbic hyperreactivity (e.g., in amygdala, insula) and
   hypoactivation of cingulate and prefrontal control regions (anterior
   cingulate cortex, orbitofrontal cortex, dorsomedial and dorsolateral
   prefrontal cortex). There is initial evidence for an effect of
   psychotherapy on neural processing of affective stimuli in patients with
   BPD. Neurofeedback training appears to be a promising tool for
   psychotherapeutic interventions on a neural level. However, more
   research is needed to investigate the effect of psychotherapy on neural
   processing in BPD. Implications for the clinical setting and future
